). Stonefish Synanceia verrucosa Bloch & Schneider, 1801 (Actinopterygii: Synanceiidae): the first record in the Syrian coast and the fourth in the Mediterranean. International Journal of Aquatic Biology, 7 (6), 383-386.\", \"Katsanevakis, S., Zenetos, A., Belchior, C. and Cardoso, A.C. (2013). Invading European Seas: Assessing pathways of introduction of marine aliens. Ocean and Coastal Management 76, 64-74.\", \"Lieske, E. and Myers, R.F. (2004): Coral reef guide; Red Sea to Gulf of Aden, South Oman. Harper Collins, London, 384 p.\", \"Maillaud, C., Hoang-Oppermann, T., Hoang-Oppermann, V., Rigot, H., Girardot, S. and Nour, M. (2020). Is stonefish Synanceia verrucosa envenomation potentially lethal? Toxicon, 184, 78-82.\", \"Myers, R.F. (1999). Micronesian reef fishes: a comprehensive guide to the coral reef fishes of Micronesia, 3rd revised and expanded edition. Coral Graphics, Barrigada, Guam, 330 p.\", \"Por, F.D. (1990). Lessepsian migration. An appraisal and new data. Bulletin of the Institute of Oceanography, Monaco, 7, 1-10.\", \"Poss, S.G. (1999). Scorpaenidae, scorpionfishes (also, lionfishes, rockfishes, stingfishes, stonefishes and waspfishes. In: Carpenter, K.E. and Niem, V. (Eds.), FAO species identification guide for fishery purposes. Vol. 4. Bony fishes, part 2 (Mugilidae to Carangidae). FAO, Rome, pp. 2291-2352.\", \"Randall, J.E. (1995). Coastal fishes of Oman. University of Hawaii Press, Honolulu, Hawaii, 439 p.\", \"Turan, C., Uyan, A., Do\\u011fdu, S. A., & Erg\\u00fcden, D. (2024a). First Record of the Blonde Ray Raja brachyura (Rajidae) on Turkish Coasts. Tethys Environmental Sciences, 1(3), 127-134.\", \"Turan, C., Erg\\u00fcden, D, G\\u00fcrlek, M. and Do\\u011fdu, S.A. (2024b). Checklist of alien fish species in the Turkish marine ichthyofauna for science and policy support. Tethys Environmental Sciences, 1(2), 50-86.\", \"Uyan, A., Turan, C., Do\\u011fdu, S. A., G\\u00fcrlek, M., Ya\\u011fl\\u0131o\\u011flu, D., & S\\u00f6nmez, B. (2024). Genetic and Some Bio-Ecological Characteristics of Lessepsian Lizardfish Saurida lessepsianus from the Northeastern Mediterranean Sea. Tethys Environmental Sciences, 1(1), 1-16.\"], \"language\": \"eng\", \"license\": \"cc-by-4.0\", \"journal_title\": \"Tethys Environmental Science\", \"journal_volume\": \"1\", \"journal_issue\": \"3\", \"journal_pages\": \"144-151\", \"imprint_publisher\": \"Tethys Environmental Science\", \"notes\": \"ISSN : 3023-7343\", \"upload_type\": \"publication\", \"publication_type\": \"article\", \"prereserve_doi\": {\"doi\": \"10.5281/zenodo.13733301\", \"recid\": 13733301}}, \"title\": \"Occurrence of the Indo-Pacific Stonefish, Synanceia verrucosa Bloch and Schneider, 1801 in the Northeastern Mediterranean Sea\", \"links\": {\"self\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/13733301\", \"html\": \"https://zenodo.org/deposit/13733301\", \"badge\": \"https://zenodo.org/badge/doi/.svg\", \"files\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/13733301/files\", \"bucket\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/files/a472e620-c5d3-4509-9b93-a2c4893dc325\", \"latest_draft\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/13733301\", \"latest_draft_html\": \"https://zenodo.org/deposit/13733301\", \"publish\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/13733301/actions/publish\", \"edit\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/13733301/actions/edit\", \"discard\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/13733301/actions/discard\", \"newversion\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/13733301/actions/newversion\", \"registerconceptdoi\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/13733301/actions/registerconceptdoi\"}, \"record_id\": 13733301, \"owner\": 1087900, \"files\": [], \"state\": \"unsubmitted\", \"submitted\": false}'),(117,'Servet Dogdu','dogduservet@gmail.com','','',0,0,'dogduservet@gmail.com','Evidence of Nursery Area and Length-Weight Relationships for Longnose Spurdog Squalus blainville in the Northeastern Mediterranean','',0,'Nursery areas are essential habitats for sharks, offering protection and increasing the survival of newborns. This study aims to investigate a potential nursery area for Squalus blainville in the Eastern Mediterranean Sea that has very scarce information in the eastern Mediterranean Sea and contributes to the length-weight relationships. We identified the location of the potential nursery area by interviewing local fishermen. We collected 48 adults and 22 embryos neonates of S. blainville specimens from the entrance of Iskenderun Bay on 03 April 2024. We recorded 48 longnose spurdog sharks in the catches ranging from 68.9 cm to 120.2 cm TL, which corresponded to mature individuals. The length-weight relations (LWR) of combined sexes of S. blainville were observed as W = 0.0005 x L3.0277 (R2 = 0.9303). Our data provide evidence to recognize Iskenderun Bay as a possible nursery area for longnose spurdog sharks, meeting all the criteria proposed to identify nursery areas. These findings constitute the first documented evidence of a longnose spurdog shark nursery area in the Iskenderun Bay in Turkish marine waters.','Longnose spurdog, Nursery area, Iskenderun Bay, length-weight relationship','Natural Science','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci_TES-1174455-R1.pdf','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci_TES-1174455-R1.docx','../paperimages/Tethys_EnvSci_TES-1174455-R1.jpg','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci_TES-1174455-R1.docx','../uploadfiles/COPYRIGHT_TES-1174455-R1.docx','','../reviewerCommentFile/Tethys_EnvSci_TES-1174455-R1.docx','0000-00-00','Your article has been accepted for publication. Thank you for choosing Tethys Environmental Science.','','','','TES-1174455-R1','TES-1174455',1,'Research Article','',0,1,0,1,1,1,0,0,'2024-12-15','2024-08-12','2024-08-12 10:22:06','2024-10-02','2024-12-07','2024-12-15','Cemal Turan*, Servet A. Doğdu, Alen Soldo','<br>Akyol, O., Şen, H. (2022). Recent observations on sandbar shark Carcharhinus plumbeus (Carchardinidae) around sea cages