ish Species in the Turkish Marine Ichthyofauna for Science and Policy Support. Tethys Environmental Science, 1(2), 50-86.\", \"Vagianou, S., Athanassopoulou, F., Rigos, G. (2006). Prevalence and pathology of ectoparasites of Mediterranean sea bream and sea bass reared under different environmental and aquaculture conditions. Israeli Journal of Aquaculture, 58(2), 78-88.\"], \"language\": \"eng\", \"license\": \"cc-by-4.0\", \"journal_title\": \"Tethys Environmental Science\", \"journal_volume\": \"2\", \"journal_issue\": \"1\", \"journal_pages\": \"24-30\", \"imprint_publisher\": \"Tethys Environmental Science\", \"notes\": \"ISSN : 3023-7343\", \"upload_type\": \"publication\", \"publication_type\": \"article\", \"prereserve_doi\": {\"doi\": \"10.5281/zenodo.15031840\", \"recid\": 15031840}}, \"title\": \"Presence and potential threats of the cymotoid isopod Ceratothoa oestroides (Risso 1816) in meagre Argyrosomus regius (Asso, 1801) caught in Mersin Bay, Northeastern Mediterranean\", \"links\": {\"self\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15031840\", \"html\": \"https://zenodo.org/deposit/15031840\", \"badge\": \"https://zenodo.org/badge/doi/.svg\", \"files\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15031840/files\", \"bucket\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/files/8e3a99cc-df87-45d3-8787-1acd5e6cd0d8\", \"latest_draft\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15031840\", \"latest_draft_html\": \"https://zenodo.org/deposit/15031840\", \"publish\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15031840/actions/publish\", \"edit\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15031840/actions/edit\", \"discard\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15031840/actions/discard\", \"newversion\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15031840/actions/newversion\", \"registerconceptdoi\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15031840/actions/registerconceptdoi\"}, \"record_id\": 15031840, \"owner\": 1087900, \"files\": [], \"state\": \"unsubmitted\", \"submitted\": false}'),(135,'Deniz Ayas','ayasdeniz@gmail.com','','',0,0,'ayasdeniz@gmail.com','Macrozoobenthic Diversity and Environmental Parameters along the Karasu Coast (Sakarya, Black Sea)','',0,'This study aims to investigate the distribution of macrozoobenthic fauna and water quality parameters in the Sakarya/Karasu coastline of the Western Black Sea coast of Turkey. Bottom sediment samples were collected from 15 different points between Sakarya River and Küçükboğaz Creek by Ekman grab method and benthic organism diversity was evaluated. Water quality parameters such as pH, conductivity, salinity, temperature, dissolved oxygen and oxygen saturation were also measured. These parameters were then analyzed in relation to the distribution of benthic species. Eight different benthic species were identified as a result of the study. Donax sp. (Linnaeus, 1758) (19%) was the most common species, while Rapana venosa (Valenciennes, 1846) (3%) was the least common species. Water quality parameters were evaluated considering the impact of Sakarya River and Küçükboğaz Stream on the region. The distribution of benthic species was found to be directly affected by breakwater structures and coastal erosion, thus contributing to the adaptation processes of species such as Mytilus galloprovincialis (Lamarck, 1819) and Donax sp. (Linnaeus, 1758). Despite the overall low species diversity of the Black Sea ecosystem, the region has an important benthic ecosystem in terms of biological productivity. This study provides a valuable reference point for longitudinal monitoring of benthic ecosystems in the western Black Sea coast and determination of habitat loss along the coastline.','Karasu,BlackSea,BenthicEcosystem,MacrozoobenthicFauna,WaterQualityParameters','Engineering Science','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci_1359759.docx','','../paperimages/image_1359759.png',NULL,'','','','0000-00-00','Dear authors, your article will be accepted for publication after minor corrections are made.','','','','TES-1359759','TES-1359759',0,'Research Article','',1,2,1,0,0,0,0,0,'2025-02-18','2025-02-18','2025-02-18 10:52:34',NULL,NULL,'0000-00-00','Deniz Ayas, Anıl Alper  AYDIN*','',0,0,'',NULL,0,1,0,0,0,'','',''),(136,'Amani mustafa','amonafitori@gmail.com','','',0,0,'amonafitori@gmail.com','Occurrence of Wahoo, Acantocybium solandri in Libya, first record from the north African coast','',0,'The present study reports the first record of two specimens of the Wahoo, Acanthocybium solandri from Libya. Other than two rather old records from southern Italy, central Mediterranean, the most recent records were caught in the eastern Mediterranean. The present reported constitutes the first records from the coast of northern Africa.','First record, Non-indigenous species, Acanthocybium solandri, Libya coast.','Natural Science','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1361323-R1.docx','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci_1361323.docx','',NULL,'../uploadfiles/COPYRIGHT_TES-1361323-R1.docx','','../reviewerCommentFile/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1361323-R1.docx','0000-00-00','Please respond to each Reviewer&#39;s corrections:\r\n\r\nReviewer 1:Dear editor, thank you\r\nThe authors report on “Occurrence of Wahoo, Acantocybium solandri in Libya, first record from the north African coast”. This is interesting research which fill a gap in the distribution and occurrence of species in Libyan water. However, some marks and comments are provided below.\r\nTitle:\r\nTitle should be changed, and consequently the documented locations of records of Acantocybium solandri in the Mediterranean; because recent study has documented the species\r\nhttps://ejabf.journals.ekb.eg/article_407425_5f00b3f635642c91668fb9c69c12e2f9.pdf\r\nDone\r\nAbstract\r\nLocation of catch, morphometr ic and meristic measurements should be mentioned accurately.\r\nThe location is given. Morphometric and meristics are not seen in the photograph and therefore not mentioned.\r\nIntroduction\r\nNeeds comprehensive literature around the study\r\nDone\r\nMaterials and Methods\r\n-	Scale (for example ruler) should be used to indicate the true length of the photographed fish.\r\nThe length of the specimens was estimated from the flour tiles on the background to be 20 cm.\r\n-	Morphometric and meristic measurements, along with identification keys, all should be provided.\r\nThe description of the specimens was only according what can be seen in the photograph and not general characters of the species.\r\nResults\r\nPhotographs and video of both fish captures off the coasts of Talamitha region, Libya. There is no videos!, the site name should be mentioned on the map.\r\nThere is no video. We believe that the red star is sufficient to indicate the location. The name of the site is mentioned in the text.\r\n \r\nThe pectoral fins are relatively short and positioned close to the head. This sentence is repeated!\r\nDone\r\nDiscussion\r\nShould de updated, because recent study has documented the species\r\nhttps://ejabf.journals.ekb.eg/article_407425_5f00b3f635642c91668fb9c69c12e2f9.pdf\r\nDone\r\nalso, discussion should imply the potential reasons for the observation of the specie in Libyan waters.\r\n?\r\n\r\n\r\nThe authors report on “Occurrence of Wahoo, Acantocybium solandri in Libya, first record from the north African coast”. This is interesting research which fill a gap in the distribution and\r\noccurrence of species in Libyan water. However, some marks and comments are provided below. Title: Title should be changed, and consequently the documented locations of records of\r\nAcantocybium solandri in the Mediterranean; because recent study has documented the species https://ejabf.journals.ekb.eg/article_407425_5f00b3f635642c91668fb9c69c12e2f9.pdf Abstract Location of catch, morphometric and meristic measurements should be mentioned accurately.\r\nIntroduction Needs comprehensive literature around the study Materials and Methods - Scale (for example ruler) should be used to indicate the true length of the photographed fish. -\r\nMorphometric and meristic measurements, along with identification keys, all should be provided. Results Photographs and video of both fish captures off the coasts of Talamitha region, Libya.\r\nThere is no videos!, the site name should be mentioned on the map. The pectoral fins are\r\nrelatively short and positioned close to the head. This sentence is repeated! Discussion Should de updated, because recent study has documented the species\r\nhttps://ejabf.journals.ekb.eg/article_407425_5f00b3f635642c91668fb9c69c12e2f9.pdf also,\r\ndiscussion should imply the potential reasons for the observation of the specie in Libyan waters.\r\n\r\n\r\nReviewer 2:\r\n\r\nReviewer 3:\r\n\r\n','','','','TES-1361323-R1','TES-1361323',0,'Research Article','',0,-2,0,1,0,0,0,0,'2025-03-09','2025-03-09','2025-03-09 23:06:00',NULL,NULL,'0000-00-00','Amani mustafa*','',0,0,'',NULL,0,1,0,0,0,'','',''),(137,'Amani mustafa','amonafitori@gmail.com','','',0,0,'amonafitori@gmail.com','First Descriptive Occurrence of the Wahoo Acantocybium solandri (Cuvier, 1832) from the Libyan Waters, Central Mediterranean','',0,'The confirmed occurrence of the wahoo Acanthocybium solandri has been reported from the marine waters of Libya. Two specimens were caught with a trammel net at a depth of 15 m off the coast of Talamitha in February 2025. The previous record of A. solandri originated from an indeterminate locality along the Libyan coast, lacking both descriptive data and photographic documentation. In this regard, this report aims to present the captured A. solandri specimens in Libyan waters with specified geographic location for the first time.','Wahoo, Acanthocybium solandri, Occurrence, Central Mediterranean, Libyan coast','Natural Science','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1373246.pdf','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1373246.docx','../paperimages/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1373246.jpg','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1373246.docx','','','','0000-00-00','De