P. A. (1998). Fleeting images dynamics of North Sea ray populations. University of Amsterdam, Faculty of Biology. Amsterdam, p 145.\", \"Yaka, U., Y\\u00fcce, R. (2006). The rough ray, Raja radula Delaroche, 1809 (Rajidae), new to the Sea of Marmara, Turkey. Zoology in the Middle East, 239, 112-114.\", \"Yarmaz, A. (2009). Some biological properties of cartilaginous fish living in Edremit Bay and their vicinity. Bal\\u0131kesir University, Institute of Science. Bal\\u0131kesir, p 159.\", \"Yeldan H. (2005). Identification of bioecological characteristics of some rays caught Raja clavata (Linnaeus, 1758), Raja asterias (Delaroche, 1809), Raja radula (Delaroche, 1809), Dasyatis pastinaca (Linnaeus, 1758) from \\u0130skenderun and Mersin Bays. \\u00c7ukurova University, Science Institute, Adana, p 153.\", \"Y\\u0131\\u011f\\u0131n, C. \\u00c7., \\u0130\\u015fmen, A. (2009). Length\\u2013weight relationships for seven rays from Saros Bay (north Aegean Sea). Journal of Applied Ichthyology, 25 (Suppl. 1), 106-108.\", \"Y\\u0131\\u011f\\u0131n, C. \\u00c7., \\u0130\\u015fmen, A. (2014). Age, growth and reproduction of the rough ray, Raja radula (Delaroche, 1809) in Saros Bay (North Aegean Sea). Journal of the Black Sea/Mediterranean Environment, 20, 213\\u02d7227.\"], \"language\": \"eng\", \"license\": \"cc-by-4.0\", \"journal_title\": \"Tethys Environmental Science\", \"journal_volume\": \"2\", \"journal_issue\": \"2\", \"journal_pages\": \"7-15\", \"imprint_publisher\": \"Tethys Environmental Science\", \"notes\": \"ISSN : 3023-7343\", \"upload_type\": \"publication\", \"publication_type\": \"article\", \"prereserve_doi\": {\"doi\": \"10.5281/zenodo.15641267\", \"recid\": 15641267}}, \"title\": \"Rare Occurrence of the Rough Ray Raja radula (Family: Rajidae) in the Northeastern Mediterranean\", \"links\": {\"self\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15641267\", \"html\": \"https://zenodo.org/deposit/15641267\", \"badge\": \"https://zenodo.org/badge/doi/.svg\", \"files\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15641267/files\", \"bucket\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/files/84745871-5150-4b84-805f-9d25f0d496fe\", \"latest_draft\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15641267\", \"latest_draft_html\": \"https://zenodo.org/deposit/15641267\", \"publish\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15641267/actions/publish\", \"edit\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15641267/actions/edit\", \"discard\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15641267/actions/discard\", \"newversion\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/15641267/actions/newversion\"}, \"record_id\": 15641267, \"owner\": 1087900, \"files\": [], \"state\": \"unsubmitted\", \"submitted\": false}'),(139,'Deniz Ayas','ayasdeniz@mersin.edu.tr','','',0,0,'ayasdeniz@mersin.edu.tr','First Documentation of Pachygrapsus marmoratus in Mersin Bay and Biotope Preference','',0,'The objective of this study is to document the first observation of the marbled crab Pachygrapsus marmoratus (Fabricius, 1787) in Mersin Bay and to ascertain its biotope preference in this region. In March 2025, benthic sampling was conducted of a single male specimen within a rocky coastal habitat characterized by a proliferation of photophilic algae. The identification of the species was based on the presence of characteristic morphological features. The specimen was subsequently preserved and deposited at the Mersin University Marine Life Museum. The findings suggest that P. marmoratus is expanding its distribution along the eastern Mediterranean coast and that this expansion may be related to environmental factors such as marine climate change and habitat suitability. The marbled crab species was observed exclusively in rocky biotopes exposed to wave action, characterized by sunlight and microbial algal cover. It was not observed in mud, sand, or artificial surface biotopes. This first documentation contributes to future studies on benthic biodiversity monitoring and coastal habitat conservation in the Northeastern Mediterranean coast.','Marbled crab, Brachyura, Mersin Bay, Distribution, Mediterranean, Türkiye ','Natural Science','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _1399997.docx','','../paperimages/image_1399997.png',NULL,'','','','0000-00-00','Dear authors, your article will be accepted for publication after major corrections are made.','','','','TES-1399997','TES-1399997',0,'Research Article','',1,4,1,0,0,0,0,0,'2025-04-18','2025-04-18','2025-04-18 10:53:05',NULL,NULL,'0000-00-00','Deniz Ayas, Sibel  Alagöz Ergüden*, Deniz Ayas, Deniz  Ergüden','',0,0,'',NULL,0,1,0,0,0,'','',''),(140,'Pavendhan         M','pmadhiva@gitam.in','','',0,0,'pmadhiva@gitam.in','Predicting Air Quality Index Based on Rainfall Patterns: A Machine Learning Approach with Mathematical Modelling','',0,'This study investigates the relationship between rainfall patterns and air quality index (AQI) in the Indian subcontinent using machine learning techniques. We developed a predictive model that incorporates rainfall data, including intensity, duration, and frequency, to forecast AQI values. Methodologically, rainfall and AQI data have been collected and preprocessed from various sources, including weather stations and air quality monitoring stations. These data were used to train and test the machine learning model, which was optimized using various techniques such as feature engineering and hyperparameter tuning. The model’s performance was evaluated using several metrics, including absolute mean error, root mean square error, and coefficient of determination. The proposed model demonstrated high accuracy in predicting AQI values, outperforming traditional statistical models. Our findings demonstrate that the predictive model can accurately forecast AQI values up to three days in advance, offering valuable insights for air quality management and policymaking, while also highlighting the significant influence of rainfall patterns, where heavy rainfall events improve air quality and dry periods lead to deterioration. The study underscores the critical role of machine learning-based models in environmental monitoring and prediction, suggesting that accurate AQI forecasts not only advance research in this field but also have vital implications for public health by helping mitigate the adverse effects of air pollution on human health.','Air quality index, rainfall patterns, machine learning, predictive modeling, environmental monitoring','Natural Science','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1400301.pdf','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1400301.docx','../paperimages/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1400301.jpg','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1400301.docx','','','','0000-00-00','Dear authors, your article will be accepted for publication after minor corrections are made.','','','','TES-1400301','TES-1400301',1,'Research Article','',1,2,1,0,1,1,0,0,'2025-06-23','2025-04-25','2025-05-14 08:33:00','2025-06-03','2025-06-14','2025-06-23','Pavendhan Madhiva* , Mallemadugula S. S. R. K. N. Sarma , Krishna Kumari','<br>Abadi, M., Barham, P., Chen, J., Chen, Z., Davis, A., Dean, J., Devin, M., Ghemawat, S., Irving, G., Isard, M., Kudlur, M., Levenberg, J., Monga, R., Moore, S., Murray, D. G., Steiner, B., Tucker, P., Vasudevan, V., Warden, P., Wicke, M., Yu, Y., Zheng, X. (2016). TensorFlow: a system for large-scale machine learning. In: Proceedings Book. 12th USENIX Symposium on Operating Systems Design and Implementation, 2-4 November 2016, Savannah, USA. pp. 265-283.\r<br>Bergstra, J., Bengio, Y. (2012). Random search for hyper-parameter optimization. Journal of Machine Learning Research, 13, 281-305.\r<br>Breiman, L. (2001). Random forests. Machine Learning, 45(1), 5-32.\r<br>Chen, T., Guestrin, C. (2016). X G Boost: A scalable tree boosting system. In: Proceedings Book. 22nd ACM SIGKDD International Conference on Knowledge Discovery and Data Mining, 13-17 August 2016, San Francisco, USA. pp. 785-794.\r<br>Chen, X., Zhang, X., Gu