verview on techniques, taxonomy, applications and research directions. SN Computer Science, 2(6), 1-20.\", \"Scarfe, W. C., Farman, A. G. (2008). What is cone-beam CT and how does it work?. Dental Clinics of North America, 52(4), 707-730.\", \"Suryani, D., Shoumi, M. N., Wakhidah, R. (2021). Object detection on dental x-ray images using deep learning method. In IOP Conference Series: Materials Science and Engineering (p. 012058). IOP Publishing.\", \"\\u00dcnsal, \\u00dc., Adem, K. (2022). Classification of caries aries level using image processing and deep learning methods on dental images. International Journal of Sivas University of Science and Technology, 2(2), 30-53.\", \"Y\\u00fcksel, A. E., G\\u00fcltekin, S., Simsar, E., \\u00d6zdemir, \\u015e. D., G\\u00fcndo\\u011far, M., Tokg\\u00f6z, S. B., Hamamc\\u0131, \\u0130. E. (2021). Dental enumeration and multiple treatment detection on panoramic X-rays using deep learning. Scientific Reports, 11(1), 12342.\", \"Zdravkovic, M., Pesic, Z., Pesic, P. (2021). Tooth detection with small panoramic radiograph images datasets and Faster RCNN model. In: Book of Proceedings. ICIST 2021 - 11th International Conference on Information Society and Technology, 7-10 March 2021, Kopaonik, Serbia. pp. 1-4.\", \"Zhang, Y., Ye, F., Chen, L., Xu, F., Chen, X., Wu, H., Cao, M., Li, Y., Wang, Y., Huang, X. (2023). Children\'s dental panoramic radiographs dataset for caries segmentation and dental disease detection. Scientific Data, 10(1), 380.\"], \"language\": \"eng\", \"license\": \"cc-by-4.0\", \"journal_title\": \"Tethys Environmental Science\", \"journal_volume\": \"2\", \"journal_issue\": \"3\", \"journal_pages\": \"122-128\", \"imprint_publisher\": \"Tethys Environmental Science\", \"notes\": \"ISSN : 3023-7343\", \"upload_type\": \"publication\", \"publication_type\": \"article\", \"prereserve_doi\": {\"doi\": \"10.5281/zenodo.17220181\", \"recid\": 17220181}}, \"title\": \"Artificial Intelligence in Dental Imaging for Disease Detection and Treatment\", \"links\": {\"self\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/17220181\", \"html\": \"https://zenodo.org/deposit/17220181\", \"badge\": \"https://zenodo.org/badge/doi/.svg\", \"files\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/17220181/files\", \"bucket\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/files/a44285b4-9f01-4ab1-ade1-75563331b378\", \"latest_draft\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/17220181\", \"latest_draft_html\": \"https://zenodo.org/deposit/17220181\", \"publish\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/17220181/actions/publish\", \"edit\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/17220181/actions/edit\", \"discard\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/17220181/actions/discard\", \"newversion\": \"https://zenodo.org/api/deposit/depositions/17220181/actions/newversion\"}, \"record_id\": 17220181, \"owner\": 1087900, \"files\": [], \"state\": \"unsubmitted\", \"submitted\": false}'),(149,'SEDA NUR GAMZE  HAMAL','sedanurgamzehamal@gmail.com','','',0,0,'sedanurgamzehamal@gmail.com','Trophic roles of species and succession process in artificial reefs in the Eastern Mediterranean','',0,'The objective of this study is to examine the stages of biological succession occurring over one year in artificial reefs deployed in Akkum Bay, Eastern Mediterranean, and to identify the trophic and functional roles of the species involved. Artificial reef modules composed of 1 × 1 m concrete blocks were deployed 100 metres offshore at a depth of 8 metres. Species distribution and density were recorded by visual census, quadrat sampling, and underwater photo-videography during monthly dives over 12 months. The collected data were classified according to succession stages. After an initial three-month period of biofilm formation, the structures were colonised by herbivorous gastropods and sessile invertebrates. Between three and six months, filter-feeding bivalves and epibiont sponges integrated into the system, while predatory molluscs appeared between six and nine months. In the final stage, fish species from multiple trophic levels were observed, including Lessepsian migrants with significant ecological impact such as Pterois miles, Apogonichthyoides pharaonis, and Siganus rivulatus. These findings show that artificial reefs function as dynamic ecosystem components, supporting both species diversity and functional trophic organisation. Monitoring species with high ecological impact highlights artificial reefs as tools for habitat restoration and as platforms for observing biogeographic transition dynamics. Long-term monitoring and integration with environmental parameters are expected to provide further evidence of the contribution of artificial reefs to ecosystem functionality.','Akkum Bay, Artificial reefs, biological succession, highly biologically effective species, Lessepsian migration.','Natural Science','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _1492253.docx','','../paperimages/image_1492253.jpg',NULL,'','','','0000-00-00','','','','','TES-1492253','TES-1492253',0,'Research Article','',1,-1,0,0,0,0,0,0,'2025-09-11','2025-09-11','2025-09-11 14:13:04',NULL,NULL,'0000-00-00','SEDA NUR GAMZE  HAMAL*, Deniz Ayas, Hayri Ertuğrul Çete, Mert Can ACAR, Ali Ulvi','',0,0,'',NULL,0,1,0,0,0,'','',''),(150,'H. Ertugrul  Cete','ertugrul_cete@hotmail.com','','',0,0,'ertugrul_cete@hotmail.com','Assessing the Bioecology of the Invasive Lionfish (Pterois spp.) in the Eastern Mediterranean Sea','',0,'ABSTRACT\r\nThe combined effect of the opening of the Suez Canal and rising sea temperatures from global climate change has driven numerous species to leave their natural habitats in search of new environments. This biogeographic shift is especially notable in the Eastern Mediterranean, where it has significantly altered regional biodiversity. The Eastern Mediterranean has become a favourable habitat for species originating from the Red Sea. One such species, the lionfish (Pterois spp.), has begun to affect fish diversity in the region as a rapidly spreading Lessepsian invasive species. The present study investigates the biology and ecology of lionfish through regular dives at four stations where dense populations were identified over a period of two years. We analyzed the length, weight, age (via scale analysis), stomach contents, and gonads of collected specimens. We also recorded environmental parameters including seawater temperature, depth, pH, and salinity. Lionfish were found at an average depth of 12.3 m, generally in rocky areas; their lengths ranged from 6 to 38 cm (average 24.48 cm) and their weights from 1.3 to 769 g (average 229.38 g). Ages ranged from 1 to 7 years (with an average of 3 years). The stomach contents were found to be predominantly composed of small fish, accounting for 77.5% of the total weight, while invertebrates constituted a smaller proportion (5.9%). The mean gonad weight of the 191 examined females was 4.52 g, with a maximum recorded weight of 60 g. The mean egg diameter was 1.3 mm, and the mean number of eggs per female was 74. Analyses of the gonadosomatic index and condition factor indicate that the reproductive period peaks during the summer months. Indicators of lionfish proliferation in the Eastern Mediterranean include venomous spines, rapid growth, early maturation, hunting success, and opportunistic feeding habits. Our findings on their rapid growth, high fecundity, and diet overlap with native predators suggest that sustainable population control may depend on identifying and protecting their natural predators, alongside targeted removal efforts.\r\n','Keywords: Invasive species, Lessepsian, Lionfish, Pterois, Eastern Mediterranean','Natural Science','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _1500240.docx','','../paperimages/image_1500240.pdf',NULL,'','','','0000-00-00','','','','','TES-1500240','TES-1500240',0,'Research Article','',1,-1,0,0,0,0,0,0,'2025-09-18','2025-09-18','2025-09-18 16:48:00',NULL,NULL,'0000-00-00','H. Ertugrul  Cete*, R. Serap Ergene','',0,0,'',NULL,0,1,0,0,0,'','',''),(151,'Pelin Özçelik','avpelinozcelik@hotmail.com','','',0,0,'avpelinozcelik@hotmail.com','Marine Pollution, MARPOL Applications and Sustainable Fishing in Mersin Province: Current Situation and Legal Recommendations','',0,'The Mediterranean Sea is defined as a semi-enclosed marine system that is becoming increasingly fragile each year due to rising ship traffic, illegal fishing, microplastic pollution, and land-based pollution (Jones et al., 2023). The province of Mersin, a major port in the Eastern Mediterranean, is located at the intersection of these multi-layered environmental pressures. It also hosts trade, tourism, and fishing activities of strategic importance. The present study is supported by qualitative data obtained from institutional interviews and field analyses conducted in Mersin in 2025; the local applicability of the MARPOL Convention, marine pollution dynamics, and sustainable fishing policies have been evaluated in a multidimensional manner.\r\nThe findings indicate that the pollutants reaching the Mersin coast are not only local but also regional and land-based. In particular, agricultural drainage, pesticides, heavy metals, and detergent residues transported via the Berdan and Seyhan rivers accumulate in coastal ecosystems, exerting pressure on marine biodiversity. This pollution load is further exacerbated by the absence of biological treatment units in existing wastewater treatment plants. Moreover, the absence of regulatory oversight in maritime domains and the constraints imposed by port infrastructure hinder the effective implementation of the MARPOL Convention.\r\nThe presence of microplastics has been detected in the digestive systems of fish and in sediments collected off the coast of Mersin. This situation demonstrates that toxic substances entering the food chain pose a threat to both the environment and public health through bioaccumulation. In the specific case of fishing, despite the implementation of digital tracking through the BAGIS system, economic pressures, a lack of educational resources, and unlicensed activities continue to result in illegal fishing. It is evident that inadequate support for the small-scale fishing community has the potential to compromise the viability of sustainability objectives.\r\nThe study further recommends that Türkiye participate more actively in regional governance mechanisms (REMPEC, UNEP/MAP, etc.) and accelerate its SECA preparations, in light of the international literature. The example of Mersin demonstrates that sustainable marine management requires not only technical and legal solutions but also the integrated planning of regional cooperation, infrastructure investments, and local awareness campaigns.','MARPOL, sustainable fishing, marine pollution, Mersin, Mediterranean Sea, port state control','Natural Science','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _1514276.docx','','../paperimages/image_1514276.png',NULL,'','../uploadfiles/Approval_1514276.pdf','','0000-00-00','','','','','TES-1514276','TES-1514276',0,'Research Article','',1,-1,0,0,0,0,0,0,'2025-09-25','2025-09-25','2025-09-25 10:42:52',NULL,NULL,'0000-00-00','Pelin Özçelik*, Selen  SERDER, Deniz AYAS','',0,0,'',NULL,0,1,0,0,0,'','',''),(152,'Servet Dogdu','dogduservet@gmail.com','','',0,0,'dogduservet@gmail.com','Population Genetics of the Short-Beaked Garfish Belone svetovidovi in Turkish Marine Waters using Mitochondrial DNA Markers','',0,'This study investigates the population genetic structure of the short-beaked garfish Belone svetovidovi across the Turkish marine coasts using two mitochondrial markers, cytochrome oxidase I and 12S ribosomal RNA. A total of 280 individuals were sampled from seven sites across the Black Sea, Marmara Sea, and Aegean Sea. Haplotype network analyses showed that COI provided greater resolution, displaying a star-like topology that points to recent population expansion, while 12S rRNA exhibited more conserved patterns, aligning with purifying selection. Tajima’s D values diverged between loci, indicating potential population structuring and demographic processes. Overall, COI captured among-basin differentiation, while 12S rRNA supported deep lineage splits. These findings highlight the complementary nature of mtDNA markers and provide baseline data for future phylogeographic and conservation studies in Belonidae species.','Belone svetovidovi, mitochondrial DNA, COI, 12S rRNA, population structure','Engineering Science','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1529487-R1.pdf','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1529487-R1.docx','../paperimages/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1529487-R1.jpg','../uploadfiles/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1529487-R1.docx','../uploadfiles/COPYRIGHT_TES-1529487-R1.docx','','../reviewerCommentFile/Tethys_EnvSci _TES-1529487-R1.docx','0000-00-00','Dear authors, we are pleased to inform you that your article has been accepted for publication in its final version. We appreciate your selection of Tethys Environmental Sciences.','','','','TES-1529487-R1','TES-1529487',1,'Research Article','',0,1,0,1,1,1,0,0,'2025-09-30','2025-05-05','2025-09-25 14:18:32','2025-08-02','2025-09-29','2025-09-30','Cemal Turan*, Petya Pavlova Ivanova, Servet Ahmet Doğdu, Deniz Ergüden, Violin Stoyanov Raykov, Maria Yankova, Deniz Yağlıoğlu, Ayşegül Ergenler, Ivelina Zlateva, Nina Stoycheva Dzhembekova','<br>Banford, H. M., Bermingham, E., Collette, B. B. (2004). Molecular phylogenetics and biogeography of transisthmian and amphi-Atlantic needlefishes (Belonidae: Strongylura and Tylosurus): perspectives on New World marine speciation. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 31(3), 833-851.\r<br>Brown, K. L. (1986). Population demographic and genetic structure of plains killifish from the Kansas and Arkansas river basins in Kansas. Transactions of the American Fisheries Society, 115(4), 568-576.\r<br>Cawthorn, D. M., Steinman, H. A., Witthuhn, R. C. (2012). Evaluation of the 16S and 12S rRNA genes as universal m